Minimal C++ framework example.

Yes—building a tiny “framework” yourself is the best way to really understand it. 
Let’s make a very small Proof of Concept (PoC) C++ framework that demonstrates:

Event loop (framework controls flow)
Registration of callbacks (your code plugs in)
Framework calling your code (Inversion of Control)

Mini C++ Framework (PoC)
#include <iostream>
#include <functional>
#include <vector>
#include <thread>
#include <chrono>

class MiniFramework {
public:
    using Task = std::function<void()>;

    void registerTask(Task task) {
        tasks_.push_back(task);
    }

    void run() {
        std::cout << "Framework started...\n";

        // Event loop (framework controls execution)
        for (int i = 0; i < 3; ++i) {
            std::cout << "Framework loop iteration: " << i << "\n";

            for (auto& task : tasks_) {
                task();  // 👈 Framework calls user code
            }

            std::this_thread::sleep_for(std::chrono::seconds(1));
        }

        std::cout << "Framework stopped.\n";
    }

private:
    std::vector<Task> tasks_;
};

User Code (Using the Framework)

int main() {
    MiniFramework app;

    // User registers logic
    app.registerTask([]() {
        std::cout << "Task 1 executed\n";
    });

    app.registerTask([]() {
        std::cout << "Task 2 executed\n";
    });

    app.run();  // 👈 Framework takes control

    return 0;
}

🔍 What this demonstrates
    Framework Responsibilities
        Controls execution → run()
        Provides extension point → registerTask()
        Calls user code → task()
    Inversion of Control
        You don’t call tasks manually
        Framework calls them inside its loop
    How this relates to real frameworks
        Like Qt → event loop + signals/slots
        Like backend frameworks → request handling loop
        Like game engines → update/render loop


